metatags.og:title: Reptile - Digestive and urogenital systems
metatags.og:description: Reptile - Digestive and urogenital systems: The digestive system of modern reptiles is similar in general plan to that of all higher vertebrates. It includes the mouth and its salivary glands, the esophagus, the stomach, and the intestine and ends in a cloaca. Of the few specializations of the reptilian digestive system, the evolution of one pair of salivary glands into poison glands in the venomous snakes is the most remarkable.  During development the embryos of higher vertebrates (reptiles, birds, and mammals) consecutively develop three separate sets of kidneys; these are arranged in longitudinal sequence in the body cavity. The first set, the pronephroi, are vestigial

items.htmlTitle: Here's why some animals have two penises
items.snippet:
Nov 6, 2014 ... Scientists have found the origin of the double penis and worked out why humans 
only have one. ... that in all animals the development of the penis is controlled by 
the cloaca - a cavity at the end of the digestive tract that serves as the bodily exit 
for an animal's digestive, urinary, and reproductive systems.

metatags.og:title: Here's Why Some Animals Have Two Penises
metatags.og:description: Scientists in the US have solved one of the biggest mysteries in evolutionary biology - how the penis develops, and why animals such as snakes and lizards have two, while mammals and birds are stuck with one.
